Package: mediawiki-dom-snapshot
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 python3-bs4,
 python3-lxml,
 python3-pil,
 python3-imagehash,
 python3-playwright
Recommends: chromium
Description: Headless DOM + asset + screenshot snapshotter for MediaWiki regression testing
 Drives a headless Chromium against a running MediaWiki instance via
 Playwright, captures per page the post-JS DOM, a viewport screenshot,
 and every external asset body indexed by sha256, then offers a
 three-axis diff (HTML text, asset content, screenshot pixel +
 perceptual-hash distance) so a refactor can be proven not to have
 changed anything visually or behaviourally.
 .
 Use case: detect HTML/CSS/JS/image changes introduced by MediaWiki
 core / extension upgrades or by site-CSS refactors. Capture a
 baseline before the change, run again after, run the diff.
 .
 Ships the page list under /etc/mediawiki-dom-snapshot/pages.conf. The
 baseline corpus and capture output are large, regenerable runtime data
 kept in the operator's private cache, not in the package.

Package: sdwdate-gui-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 python3-pyqt5,
 sdwdate-gui
Suggests: xvfb,
 stalonetray,
 xdotool,
 x11-utils,
 weston,
 qtwayland5,
 python3-coverage
Description: Regression tests and fuzzer for the sdwdate-gui applet
 Headless test suite for sdwdate-gui-server. Drives the real
 SdwdateTrayIcon and SdwdateGuiClient classes under the Qt offscreen
 platform plugin, so most of it needs neither an X server, a system
 tray, nor a live qrexec connection.
 .
 Unit coverage ('sdwdate-gui-tests' command): the client de-duplication
 invariant that keeps a Qubes VM from being listed more than once in the
 tray menu when it reconnects (Qubes authenticated-qrexec-name and
 non-Qubes self-reported-name branches), tray menu activation (left- and
 right-click open the menu; the Wayland opt-out), and wire-protocol
 regressions (a fragmented message must not hang the parser, a newline in
 a status message must not get the client kicked).
 .
 Fuzzer ('sdwdate-gui-tests-fuzz' command): a simulator that drives the
 server over a real local socket with a directed corpus plus random and
 mutated byte streams and random client-lifecycle sequences, for both the
 Qubes and non-Qubes paths. It checks for hangs, crashes, duplicate
 names, failed registration / de-registration, and stuck menus, and (with
 python3-coverage) reports line coverage of the server. The RNG seed is
 printed so any finding is reproducible.
 .
 Integration coverage ('sdwdate-gui-tests-integration' command): the same
 tray menu driven end to end on a real display -- a headless Xvfb with an
 XEmbed systray host for genuine left- and right-click delivery, and a
 headless Wayland compositor for the Wayland opt-out. These need the
 tooling in Suggests (xvfb, stalonetray, xdotool, x11-utils, weston,
 qtwayland5); any phase whose tooling is absent is skipped, not failed.
 .
 All commands require the 'sdwdate-gui' package, as the tests import its
 server module.

Package: privleap-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 privleap,
 sudo
Suggests: python3-coverage
Description: Security regression tests and fuzzers for the privleap privilege manager
 In-process security suite ('privleap-tests' command, no root): drives the
 REAL privleap code over exactly the surface an unprivileged local user can
 reach through their comm socket -- the place a bug could become arbitrary
 code execution as root.
 .
 The wire-protocol parser fuzzer wraps a server-side privleap session around a
 socketpair and feeds it a directed corpus plus random, structured, and
 mutational byte streams, asserting that every input is either parsed into a
 message type legal for that socket (with re-validated fields) or cleanly
 rejected -- never a crash, a hang (watchdog-guarded), or a type confusion --
 and that all valid traffic round-trips. The authorization-engine property
 test builds actions from the real account database and checks authorize_user
 against an independent reference model over thousands of randomized
 action/caller pairs, with the explicit invariant that a non-root caller is
 never authorized without a matching user or group rule, plus oracle-hardening
 (an unknown action and a forbidden one are indistinguishable).
 .
 Randomized fuzzer ('privleap-tests-fuzz' command, no root): the same parser
 fuzzer with a random seed and, when python3-coverage is present, a coverage
 report of the privleap library. The seed is printed so any finding is
 reproducible.
 .
 Live-daemon end-to-end test ('privleap-tests-e2e' command, needs sudo): runs
 the real privleapd and a real comm-socket client inside a private mount
 namespace (fresh tmpfs over /run and /etc/privleap, so the host's privleapd,
 state, and config are never touched and cleanup is automatic), proving end to
 end that an unauthorized action is never executed, an authorized one is, and
 a malformed-frame barrage neither crashes nor corrupts the daemon's
 authorization.
 .
 The tests target the installed privleap by default; set PRIVLEAP_REPO to run
 them against a derivative-maker checkout instead.

Package: onion-grater-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 python3-yaml,
 python3-stem,
 python3-psutil,
 onion-grater
Suggests: tor,
 bitcoind
Description: Regression and reproduction tests for the onion-grater control-port filter
 In-process unit / reproduction suite ('onion-grater-tests' command): imports
 the real onion-grater filtering code and replays each application's Tor
 control command sequence, asserting legitimate commands are allowed and
 argument-injection variants are blocked. It also reproduces the fixed Bisq
 SETCONF deanonymization (a control-port argument-injection vulnerability) and
 the follow-up DEL_ONION / HSFETCH / onion_client_auth_add / AUTHCHALLENGE
 hardening, old-vs-new, through the same matcher. No root, no network, no real
 Tor; validated non-vacuous against the pre-fix tree.
 .
 Full-stack end-to-end ('onion-grater-tests-e2e' command): a throwaway offline
 tor plus the real onion-grater binary plus a control client over the veth
 network, proving the deanonymization vector reaches Tor on the old profile and
 is blocked (510) on the new one. Needs tor and sudo (only the privileged
 setup steps are sudo'd, and they are cleaned up).
 .
 Also under /usr/share/onion-grater-tests: a real-application driver
 (bitcoind_drive.py, which drives real bitcoind through the filter) and
 adversarial security probes (probe_bypass.py, probe_rewrite.py, verify_dos.py)
 that fuzz the filter for protocol bypasses and the partial-line busy-loop DoS.
 These need sudo and tor; see the README.
 .
 The tests target the installed onion-grater by default; set ONION_GRATER_REPO
 to run them against a derivative-maker checkout instead.
